{"id":"measuring-length-motion-6","label":"Measurement of Length and Motion","lockAfter":2,"list":[{"id":"notes","type":"passage","label":"Notes","data":{"title":"Measurement of Length and Motion","text":"Several systems of units evolved with time in different parts of the world. However, when people started travelling from one place to another, it created a lot of confusion. This led to different countries coming together and adopting a set of standard units of measurement. The system of units now used is known as the ‘International System of Units’ or SI units. The SI unit of length is metre. Its symbol is m.\n        A metre scale is divided into 100 equal divisions. Each division is called a centimetre (cm). 1 cm length is further divided into 10 equal parts. Each smaller part is called a millimetre (mm). 1 mm is the smallest value of length that you can measure using this scale. 1 mm is equal to one-tenth of a centimeter (1 mm = 0.1 cm)\nFor measuring larger lengths, we use a larger unit called a kilometre (km) which is equal to 1000 metres. \nIn some scales, you might have noticed another scale marking. This scale marking is in inches, where 1 inch = 2.54 cm. In earlier days, units, such as inch and foot, were used to measure length. These units are still used by some people.\n# Right Tool\nFor measuring any length, we need an appropriate scale. For example, if you want to measure the length of your pencil, you may use a 15-cm scale. Similarly, if the height of a room is to be measured, you may need a metre scale or a measuring tape. \n# Eye position\nif you are trying to measure the length of a pencil by aligning it with a scale, the position of your eye should be directly above the tip of the pencil.\n# Measuring curved line\nIn the case of a curved line, measurements can be made with the help of a flexible measuring tape or by using a thread. The thread can then be straightened and its length can be measured using a metre scale. \n# Reference point\nWhen distance is stated with respect to a fixed object or point, then this point is called a reference point. An object is said to be in motion if its position changes with respect to the reference point with time. If an object is not changing its position with respect to the reference point with time, it is said to be at rest.\n# Linear motion\nWhen an object moves along a straight line, its motion is called linear motion. \n# Circular motion\nWhen an object moves along a circular path, its motion is called circular motion. Tie an eraser (or a potato) to one end of a thread. Hold the other end of the thread with your hand and whirl it. The eraser will follow a circular motion. eg: giant wheel, \n# Oscillatory motion\nWhen an object moves to and fro about some fixed position, its motion is called oscillatory motion. eg: swing, pendulum\n# Periodic motion\nIf an object repeats its path after a fixed interval of time, its motion is said to be periodic. When an object is in circular motion, it moves along the circular path again and again. An object in oscillatory motion also repeats its motion while moving to and fro. Both circular and oscillatory motion are periodic in nature.\n"}},{"label":"Fill in the blanks","type":"matchByDragDrop","id":"fillup","onlyBigScreen":true,"commonData":{"dashWidth":100,"actWidth":1300,"fontSize":"2rem","dashHeight":"2.7rem","labelsOnSide":true},"data":["A metre scale is divided into 100 *equal* divisions. Each division is called a *centimetre*. For measuring larger lengths, we use a larger unit called a *kilometre*.\nIn common scales, we also have another unit called *inches*.\nWhen distance is stated with respect to a fixed object or point, then this point is called *reference* point.","An object moving along a straight like has *linear* motion.\nA giant wheel when moving, has *circular* motion.\nThe pendulum of a clock has *oscillatory* motion.\nAn object that repeats its path after a fixed interval of time is called *periodic* motion.","The distance between Delhi and Lucknow is measured in *kilometre*.\nThe thickness of a coin is measured in *millimetre*.\nThe length of an eraser is measured in *centimetre*.\nThe length of the school ground is measured in *metre*."]},{"id":"mcq","label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","data":{"questions":[{"qText":"Which of the following is a standard unit for measuring length?","options":"feet, handspan, arm span, cubit"},{"qText":"Which of the following unit is not part of SI units for measuring length?","options":"inch, centimeter, meter, kilometer"},{"qText":"The length and breadth of a playground is usually mentioned in ____.","options":"metre, kilometre, millimetre, centimetre"},{"qText":"In which of the following motion, the object doesn't reach the starting point?","options":"linear motion, circular motion, oscillatory motion, periodic motion"},{"qText":"The distance is always measure with respect to a ______.","options":"reference point, starting point, ending point, person's position"}]}},{"label":"True or False","id":"true-false","type":"classifySentence","data":{"title":"Classify the below sentences as true and false","types":[{"name":"True","text":"An object is said to be in motion if its position changes with respect to the reference point with time. \nA person travelling in a train, is at rest with reference to the train. "},{"name":"False","text":"A person travelling in a car, is at rest with reference to the road.\nIt is not possible to measure the length of a curved path.\nOscillatory motion is also known as periodic motion. | Osciallatory motion is a type of periodic motion."}]}},{"id":"match","label":"Match equal length","type":"match","data":{"text":"2 m , 200 cm\n20 cm , 0.2 m\n20 mm , 2 cm\n200 m , 0.2 km\n2000 m , 2 km","title":"Match equal length"}},{"id":"slide","type":"slides2","label":"Slides: Measuring Length","data":{"title":"Measuring Length","displayType":"steps","images":"img/science/big/measuring-length-6","imgHeight":400,"fontSize":"1.5rem","steps":[{"text":"In the ancient time, different non-standard units were used to measure length. As they vary from people to people, there was confusion. They got different numbers for the same length.","img":"non-standard-units"},{"text":"We have to use the right measuring tools, and right units. For measuring the length of small objects, we can use a small scale, and units can be cm or mm. For measuring the length of a land, we should use measuring tape, and units can be metre.","img":"measuring-tools"},{"text":"When an object moves along a straight line, its motion is called linear motion. ","img":"linear-motion"},{"text":"When an object moves along a circular path, its motion is called circular motion.","img":"giant-wheel"},{"text":"When an object moves to-and-fro about some fixed position, its motion is called oscillatory motion.","img":"swing"}]}}]}